## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code uses two patterns that won't work in .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed)
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(work, cts.Token)
                             .WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken caused cancellation, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Work doesn't magically stop.** This is the biggest difference. `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread; `CancellationToken` is *cooperative*. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop that never checks the token, `WaitAsync` will throw on timeout but **the work keeps running on the thread pool**. To actually stop:

```csharp
// Pass the token INTO the work so it can cooperate
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => {
        foreach (var item in hugeList)
        {
            cts.Token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // ← checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return result;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. If the work truly can't cooperate** (third-party library, native call), the only safe option is a separate process with `Process.Kill()`. There is no .NET 8 equivalent of forcible thread termination.

**3. Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** Leaking it causes timer leaks. The original code had no disposable resources — the new code does.

**4. Exception behavior changed.** The original threw `AggregateException` wrapping the inner error. `Task.Run` + `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps and throws the inner exception directly. If callers depend on `AggregateException`, wrap explicitly:

```csharp
catch (Exception ex) when (ex is not OperationCanceledException)
{
    throw new AggregateException(ex); // preserve old behavior if needed
}
```

**5. `default(T)` return value on abort is gone** — and that's a good thing. The original code had a subtle bug: if the thread was aborted, `result` stayed `default(T)` but the abort path threw `TimeoutException`, so it was unreachable. The new code is cleaner.

### Quick Reference

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (cooperative) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested`, continue if desired |
